/s/kacy2v","comments_url":"https://lobste.rs/s/kacy2v/ios_27_system_prompts"},{"short_id":"ebtqkn","created_at":"2026-06-09T13:21:36.000-05:00","title":"Programming Languages Course Reboot","url":"https://docs.google.com/document/d/e/2PACX-1vQpgkUp1FOpgECqlyhysTBqcdvLPAtdI5SI4yCHJ82agRnsE6b5vMgsCTxgclnDqbs5PYMV7UOVkNoT/pub","score":1,"flags":0,"comment_count":0,"description":"\u003cp\u003eAdditional context: \u003ca href=\"https://bsky.app/profile/shriram.bsky.social/post/3mnufmn6mt226\" rel=\"ugc\"\u003ehttps://bsky.app/profile/shriram.bsky.social/post/3mnufmn6mt226\u003c/a\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n","description_plain":"Additional context: https://bsky.app/profile/shriram.bsky.social/post/3mnufmn6mt226","submitter_user":"priime","user_is_author":false,"tags":["education","plt"],"short_id_url":"https://lobste.rs/s/ebtqkn","comments_url":"https://lobste.rs/s/ebtqkn/programming_languages_course_reboot"},{"short_id":"vvr1qs","created_at":"2026-06-09T13:00:45.000-05:00","title":"How to Declare a C++ Function that Takes a Blob of Memory?","url":"https://giodicanio.com/2026/06/05/how-to-declare-a-c-plus-plus-function-that-takes-a-blob-of-memory/","score":2,"flags":0,"comment_count":0,"description":"","description_plain":"","submitter_user":"raymii","user_is_author":false,"tags":["c","c++"],"short_id_url":"https://lobste.rs/s/vvr1qs","comments_url":"https://lobste.rs/s/vvr1qs/how_declare_c_function_takes_blob_memory"},{"short_id":"5hxwqt","created_at":"2026-06-09T12:14:31.000-05:00","title":"Claude Fable 5 and Claude Mythos 5","url":"https://www.anthropic.com/news/claude-fable-5-mythos-5","score":1,"flags":7,"comment_count":0,"description":"","description_plain":"","submitter_user":"mattwatson","user_is_author":false,"tags":["ai"],"short_id_url":"https://lobste.rs/s/5hxwqt","comments_url":"https://lobste.rs/s/5hxwqt/claude_fable_5_claude_mythos_5"},{"short_id":"1muhxh","created_at":"2026-06-09T11:49:44.000-05:00","title":"Writing Code vs. Shipping Code: Productivity Effects Across Generations of AI Coding Tools","url":"https://www.nber.org/system/files/working_papers/w35275/w35275.pdf","score":1,"flags":0,"comment_count":0,"description":"\u003cp\u003eAbstract:\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cblockquote\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eHow do the productivity effects of AI evolve across successive generations of tools, and to what extent do task-level gains ultimately translate into final output? We study these questions in the context of software development, using data on more than 100,000 GitHub developers combined with their AI usage telemetry. In a matched event study design, we find that autocomplete, interactive coding agents, and autonomous coding agents each significantly increase coding activity (“commits”), with respective cumulative effects of 40%, 140%, and 180%. These gains, however, attenuate sharply across the production hierarchy: the 180% cumulative effect falls to 50% for the number of projects, and to 30% for actual releases. This pattern is consistent with the weak-link hypothesis: the strong productivity gains from AI are attenuated by human bottlenecks in the production chain, with an estimated elasticity of substitution of 0.25 between AI and human effort, which indicates strong complementarities. We further confirm these results across four major app marketplaces, finding a moderate increase in the number of new apps but no increase in total usage. Large task-level AI productivity gains have therefore translated only partially into shipped and used software thus far.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003c/blockquote\u003e\n","description_plain":"Abstract:\r\n\r\n\u003e How do the productivity effects of AI evolve across successive generations of tools, and to what extent do task-level gains ultimately translate into final output? We study these questions in the context of software development, using data on more than 100,000 GitHub developers combined with their AI usage telemetry. In a matched event study design, we find that autocomplete, interactive coding agents, and autonomous coding agents each significantly increase coding activity (“commits”), with respective cumulative effects of 40%, 140%, and 180%. These gains, however, attenuate sharply across the production hierarchy: the 180% cumulative effect falls to 50% for the number of projects, and to 30% for actual releases. This pattern is consistent with the weak-link hypothesis: the strong productivity gains from AI are attenuated by human bottlenecks in the production chain, with an estimated elasticity of substitution of 0.25 between AI and human effort, which indicates strong complementarities. We further confirm these results across four major app marketplaces, finding a moderate increase in the number of new apps but no increase in total usage. Large task-level AI productivity gains have therefore translated only partially into shipped and used software thus far.","submitter_user":"sunflowerseastar","user_is_author":false,"tags":["pdf","vibecoding"],"short_id_url":"https://lobste.rs/s/1muhxh","comments_url":"https://lobste.rs/s/1muhxh/writing_code_vs_shipping_code"},{"short_id":"fpgqm0","created_at":"2026-06-09T11:40:11.000-05:00","title":"An open letter to office suite users, just before the Euro-Office announcement","url":"https://blog.documentfoundation.org/blog/2026/06/08/an-open-letter/","score":20,"flags":0,"comment_count":4,"description":"","description_plain":"","submitter_user":"quobit","user_is_author":false,"tags":["release"],"short_id_url":"https://lobste.rs/s/fpgqm0","comments_url":"https://lobste.rs/s/fpgqm0/open_letter_office_suite_users_just"},{"short_id":"ncunjo","created_at":"2026-06-09T11:32:50.000-05:00","title":"Property Graphs","url":"https://www.postgresql.org/docs/19/ddl-property-graphs.html","score":12,"flags":0,"comment_count":1,"description":"","description_plain":"","submitter_user":"koala","user_is_author":false,"tags":["databases"],"short_id_url":"https://lobste.rs/s/ncunjo","comments_url":"https://lobste.rs/s/ncunjo/prope